hook.real_world_problem:
Your app needs live Bitcoin prices. Or stock data. Or weather. Or to send a payment via Razorpay's API. All of these are HTTP calls:

```
GET https://api.coindesk.com/v1/bpi/currentprice.json
→ {"bpi":{"USD":{"rate_float":45123.78}}}
```

Before Java 11, you needed Apache HttpClient (third-party) or URLConnection (clunky):
```java
// Old way — URLConnection (ugly):
URL url = new URL("https://api.example.com/data");
HttpURLConnection conn = (HttpURLConnection) url.openConnection();
conn.setRequestMethod("GET");
int code = conn.getResponseCode();
BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(conn.getInputStream()));
// ... more boilerplate ...
```

**Java 11+ HttpClient — clean and modern:**
```java
HttpClient client = HttpClient.newHttpClient();
HttpRequest request = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
    .uri(URI.create("https://api.coindesk.com/v1/bpi/currentprice.json"))
    .GET()
    .build();
HttpResponse<String> response = client.send(request,
    HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString());

if (response.statusCode() == 200) {
    JsonNode root = mapper.readTree(response.body());
    double price = root.path("bpi").path("USD").path("rate_float").asDouble();
    System.out.println("BTC: $" + price);
}
```

Fluent builder API, immutable requests, built-in HTTP/2 support, async with CompletableFuture. This is the standard in modern Java.

concept_explanation.httpclient_creation:
**Creating an HttpClient:**

```java
import java.net.http.*;
import java.net.URI;
import java.time.Duration;

// Simple client (uses default settings):
HttpClient client = HttpClient.newHttpClient();

// Configured client:
HttpClient client = HttpClient.newBuilder()
    .version(HttpClient.Version.HTTP_2)     // prefer HTTP/2, fallback to HTTP/1.1
    .connectTimeout(Duration.ofSeconds(10)) // connection timeout
    .followRedirects(HttpClient.Redirect.NORMAL)  // follow 3xx redirects
    .build();

// HttpClient is thread-safe — create ONCE, reuse everywhere:
public class ApiClient {
    private static final HttpClient HTTP = HttpClient.newBuilder()
        .connectTimeout(Duration.ofSeconds(10))
        .build();
    private static final ObjectMapper MAPPER = new ObjectMapper();
    // ...
}
```

HttpClient is expensive to create (manages connection pools, thread pools). Create once as a static field.

concept_explanation.http_request:
**Building HTTP requests:**

```java
// GET request:
HttpRequest getReq = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
    .uri(URI.create("https://api.example.com/products"))
    .GET()
    .timeout(Duration.ofSeconds(5))  // per-request timeout
    .header("Accept", "application/json")
    .build();

// POST with JSON body:
String jsonBody = "{\"name\":\"Mouse\",\"price\":799}";
HttpRequest postReq = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
    .uri(URI.create("https://api.example.com/products"))
    .POST(HttpRequest.BodyPublishers.ofString(jsonBody))
    .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
    .header("Accept",       "application/json")
    .build();

// PUT (update):
HttpRequest putReq = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
    .uri(URI.create("https://api.example.com/products/123"))
    .PUT(HttpRequest.BodyPublishers.ofString(updateJson))
    .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
    .build();

// DELETE:
HttpRequest deleteReq = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
    .uri(URI.create("https://api.example.com/products/123"))
    .DELETE()
    .build();
```

concept_explanation.http_response:
**Sending requests and reading responses:**

```java
// Synchronous send (blocks until response arrives):
HttpResponse<String> response = client.send(
    request,
    HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString()  // response body as String
);

// Response properties:
int statusCode = response.statusCode();   // 200, 404, 500 etc.
String body    = response.body();          // response body as String
HttpHeaders headers = response.headers(); // response headers
String contentType = headers.firstValue("Content-Type").orElse("unknown");

// Other BodyHandlers:
HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString()      // body as String
HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofBytes()       // body as byte[]
HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofFile(path)    // body saved directly to file
HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.discarding()    // ignore body (for DELETE etc.)

// Check status and handle:
if (response.statusCode() >= 200 && response.statusCode() < 300) {
    // Success
} else if (response.statusCode() == 404) {
    System.err.println("Resource not found");
} else if (response.statusCode() >= 500) {
    System.err.println("Server error: " + response.statusCode());
}
```

concept_explanation.auth_headers:
**Authentication — the two most common patterns:**

```java
// Bearer token (JWT — most common for REST APIs):
HttpRequest request = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
    .uri(URI.create("https://api.razorpay.com/v1/orders"))
    .GET()
    .header("Authorization", "Bearer " + jwtToken)
    .header("Accept", "application/json")
    .build();

// API key in header:
HttpRequest apiKeyReq = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
    .uri(URI.create("https://api.weather.example.com/current"))
    .GET()
    .header("X-API-Key", apiKey)
    .build();

// Basic auth (username:password base64-encoded):
import java.util.Base64;
String credentials = Base64.getEncoder()
    .encodeToString((username + ":" + password).getBytes());
HttpRequest basicReq = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
    .uri(URI.create("https://api.example.com/secure"))
    .GET()
    .header("Authorization", "Basic " + credentials)
    .build();

// Query parameters (appended to URL):
String url = "https://api.example.com/search?q=laptop&limit=10&page=1";
HttpRequest searchReq = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
    .uri(URI.create(url))
    .GET()
    .build();
```

concept_explanation.error_handling:
**Error handling patterns:**

```java
try {
    HttpResponse<String> response = client.send(request,
        HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString());

    switch (response.statusCode()) {
        case 200, 201 -> handleSuccess(response.body());
        case 400       -> throw new IllegalArgumentException("Bad request: " + response.body());
        case 401, 403  -> throw new SecurityException("Auth error: " + response.statusCode());
        case 404       -> System.out.println("Resource not found");
        case 429       -> System.out.println("Rate limited — retry after: " +
                              response.headers().firstValue("Retry-After").orElse("unknown"));
        default        -> System.err.println("HTTP error " + response.statusCode());
    }
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.err.println("Network error: " + e.getMessage());
} catch (InterruptedException e) {
    Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
    System.err.println("Request interrupted");
}
```

**IOException** is thrown for network failures (connection refused, DNS resolution failure). **InterruptedException** if the thread is interrupted while waiting. Always handle both.

concept_explanation.post_json:
**POST with Jackson-serialized body:**

```java
ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();

// Serialize request body with Jackson:
OrderRequest orderReq = new OrderRequest("Mouse", 2, 799.0);
String requestJson = mapper.writeValueAsString(orderReq);

HttpRequest request = HttpRequest.newBuilder()
    .uri(URI.create("https://api.example.com/v1/orders"))
    .POST(HttpRequest.BodyPublishers.ofString(requestJson))
    .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
    .header("Authorization", "Bearer " + token)
    .build();

HttpResponse<String> response = client.send(request,
    HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString());

// Parse response with Jackson:
if (response.statusCode() == 201) {
    OrderResponse order = mapper.readValue(response.body(), OrderResponse.class);
    System.out.println("Order created: " + order.getId());
} else {
    ErrorResponse error = mapper.readValue(response.body(), ErrorResponse.class);
    System.err.println("Error: " + error.getMessage());
}
```

